MANAGER: PUBLIC PROGRAMMES 
DEPARTMENT: Community Development 
BRANCH: Arts, Culture and Heritage 
DESIGNATION: Manager: Public Programmes 
REMUNERATION: R44 693,36 pm (basic salary, excluding benefits) 
LOCATION: cnr King George & Klein Street, Joubert Park, Johannesburg 

Minimum Requirements: 
Bachelor’s degree in Museum Studies, Arts, or Marketing or Project Management at NQF level 7; 
5 – 7 years experience working in arts, culture and heritage programmes, experiential knowledge of public programmes in the heritage sector and/or creative industries, cultural development, marketing and promotions of public programmes; 
Valid driver’s license. 

Primary Function:
Manage the public programmes for museums of the Directorate. Coordinate the design and implementation of museum programmes of the City. Coordinate the virtual programmes for museums and galleries. Manage and coordinate museum programmes in various museums and galleries. Interface with all Chief Curators on the public programmes for the respective museums. Coordinate the marketing and publicity of museum programmes and coordinate the marketing platforms for museums and galleries. Track, collate and report on visitor numbers to public programmes within museums. Liaise with stakeholders and mobilise resources for museums and galleries. Contribute to the museum policy development in the Directorate. 

Key Performance Areas: 
Manage the public programmes for museums of the Directorate; 
Coordinate the design and implementation of museum programmes of the City; 
Coordinate the virtual programmes for museums and galleries; 
Manage and coordinate museum programmes in various museums and galleries; 
Supervise the staff responsible for public programmes in museums; 
Manage the marketing and publicity of public programmes and coordinate the marketing platforms for museum and galleries; 
Liaise with stakeholders in the Museum and Heritage Sectors; 
Contribute to the cultural policy making in the Directorate; 
Manage budgets and expenditure for specified heritage and museum projects; 
Write reports to Council; 
Provide input to the budgeting process. 

Leading Competencies: 
Computer literacy (MS Office Packages, including Word, Excel, PowerPoint); 
Database skills; 
Marketing skills; 
Good written and oral communication skills in English and must be able to communicate and coordinate effectively with other stakeholders; 
Attention to detail and high levels of accuracy and excellent planning, organising, coordinating and time management skills. 

Core Competencies: 
Knowledge of arts, culture and heritage development and public programmes; 
Programme Design and Implementation; 
Marketing and Promotion of arts, culture and heritage programmes; 
Managing and promotion of Flagship Heritage Programmes; 
Knowledge of online and virtual programming in the arts, culture and heritage; 
Collaborative/Teamwork, Values and Integrity, Attention to detail, and quality-focused; 
Customer and Service Delivery Management (Batho Pele) Ethics, Professionalism; 
Impact and Influence according to City’s protocols, legislation, and standards. 

“All suitably qualified candidates are encouraged to apply and will be considered. The City of Johannesburg applies the principles of employment equity as per National legislation and policy guidelines and will consider designated groups in line with these requirements. Preference will be given to previously disadvantaged groups including those with disabilities. Appointments will be made in accordance with the approved Employment Equity Plan to promote its equitable representation in terms of race, gender and disability.” 

